        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# The Histogram That Tells You Everything {.centered}\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## A Picture Worth 10,000 Tests\n",
        "\n",
        "Look at a $p$-value histogram from a gene expression study comparing two cancer subtypes:\n",
        "\n",
        "- The **flat part** (uniform across $[0,1]$) represents null genes — no real signal\n",
        "- The **spike near 0** represents true discoveries — genes that actually differ\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "You can *see* $\\pi_0$ (the proportion of true nulls) directly: it's the height of the flat part.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "This remarkably simple observation — that the histogram itself encodes the answer — is the foundation of everything in this lecture. But turning visual intuition into a rigorous procedure took decades.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Recap from Lecture 1\n",
        "\n",
        "- High-dimensional data: $p \\gg n$\n",
        "- Multiple testing: $m$ simultaneous tests generate many false positives\n",
        "- FWER (Bonferroni) is too conservative for discovery settings\n",
        "- FDR = $E[V / (R \\vee 1)]$ is the right error metric\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**This lecture**: How to control FDR, and the deeper theory behind it.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) Procedure\n",
        "\n",
        "Given $m$ hypothesis tests with $p$-values $p_1, \\ldots, p_m$:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Order the $p$-values: $p_{(1)} \\leq p_{(2)} \\leq \\cdots \\leq p_{(m)}$\n",
        "2. Find the largest $k$ such that $p_{(k)} \\leq \\frac{k}{m} \\alpha$\n",
        "3. Reject all $H_{0(i)}$ for $i = 1, \\ldots, k$\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**Theorem** (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995): Under independence, $\\text{FDR} \\leq \\frac{m_0}{m} \\alpha \\leq \\alpha$.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## BH: Geometric Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "Plot $p_{(i)}$ vs. $i/m$. The BH procedure finds the rightmost point where the $p$-value curve dips below the line $y = \\alpha \\cdot x$."
      ],
