        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## BH Under Dependence\n",
        "\n",
        "The original BH result assumes independence of test statistics. In genomics, genes are often correlated.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**Benjamini & Yekutieli (2001)**: Under arbitrary dependence, replace $\\alpha$ with $\\alpha / \\sum_{i=1}^m 1/i \\approx \\alpha / \\ln(m)$.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**But**: Under positive regression dependency on a subset (PRDS)---a condition often satisfied in practice---the original BH procedure still controls FDR at level $\\alpha$.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# The Prior You Didn't Know You Had {.centered}\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Stein's Paradox: Borrowing Strength\n",
        "\n",
        "In 1956, Charles Stein proved something that stunned the statistics world:\n",
        "\n",
        "**The sample mean is inadmissible for estimating 3 or more means simultaneously.**\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "Efron & Morris (1977) made this concrete with baseball. To predict a batter's end-of-season average, you do better by **shrinking each player's early-season average toward the grand mean of all players** — even though the players have nothing to do with each other.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "The James-Stein estimator (James & Stein, 1961): $\\hat{\\theta}_i^{JS} = \\bar{y} + \\left(1 - \\frac{(d-3)\\sigma^2}{\\sum_j (y_j - \\bar{y})^2}\\right)(y_i - \\bar{y})$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $d \\geq 4$ is the number of means being estimated.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the founding insight of **empirical Bayes**: the other observations tell you something about the observation you're looking at. Efron took this idea and ran with it — from baseball averages to 10,000 genes.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## From Baseball to Genes\n",
        "\n",
        "In classical statistics, you test each gene in isolation. Gene #4,237 knows nothing about genes #1–4,236.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "Efron realized: when you test 10,000 genes simultaneously, the **other 9,999 results tell you something about the gene you're looking at** — just as the other batters' averages improve your estimate of any single batter.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "If most genes show no signal, then the prior probability that *any particular* gene is non-null is low. The data itself reveals the prior — without you having to specify one.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "> \"Letting the data determine the prior turns Bayesian inference from a subjective into a largely objective technique.\" — Efron, *Large-Scale Inference*, Ch. 1\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Storey's Approach: Estimating $\\pi_0$\n",
        "\n",
        "BH controls FDR at level $\\frac{m_0}{m}\\alpha$, which is conservative when $m_0 < m$.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Storey (2002)**: Estimate $\\pi_0 = m_0/m$ and use an adaptive threshold.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a tuning parameter $\\lambda$ (e.g., $\\lambda = 0.5$):\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\hat{\\pi}_0(\\lambda) = \\frac{\\#\\{p_i > \\lambda\\}}{m(1 - \\lambda)}$$\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**Intuition**: $p$-values above $\\lambda$ are mostly from true nulls (which are uniform). Count them.\n",
        "\n",
        "The R package `qvalue` implements this with automatic $\\lambda$ selection.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The $q$-value\n",
        "\n",
        "**Definition** (Storey, 2003): The $q$-value of test $i$ is the minimum FDR at which test $i$ would be called significant.\n",
        "\n",
        "$$q_i = \\min_{t \\geq p_i} \\widehat{\\text{FDR}}(t)$$\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "Analogous to a $p$-value, but for FDR instead of Type I error:\n",
        "\n",
        "- $p$-value: \"If I reject this one test, what's the false positive probability?\"\n",
        "- $q$-value: \"If I reject all tests at least this significant, what fraction are false positives?\"\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Efron's Two-Groups Model\n",
        "\n",
        "A more foundational perspective (Efron, 2004, *JASA*; developed fully in Efron, 2008, *Statistical Science*; and Efron, 2010, *Large-Scale Inference*, Ch. 2–4).\n",
        "\n",
        "Each of the $m$ cases belongs to one of two groups:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Null group** (proportion $\\pi_0$): $z_i \\sim f_0(z)$, typically $N(0,1)$\n",
        "- **Non-null group** (proportion $1 - \\pi_0$): $z_i \\sim f_1(z)$\n",
        "\n",
        "The **mixture density** of the observed $z$-scores is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$f(z) = \\pi_0 f_0(z) + (1 - \\pi_0) f_1(z)$$\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Estimating the Mixture\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key idea\n",
        "\n",
        "We observe $m$ $z$-scores. With $m$ large (thousands), we can **estimate** $f(z)$ nonparametrically.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**Efron's approach**:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Estimate $f(z)$ from a histogram or density estimate of the observed $z$-scores\n",
        "2. Assume $f_0$ is known (or estimate it---the \"empirical null\")\n",
        "3. Estimate $\\pi_0$ from the central peak of the histogram\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "This is **empirical Bayes**: we use the aggregate data to estimate the prior, then apply Bayes' rule case by case.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Local False Discovery Rate\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{fdr}(z) = P(\\text{null} \\mid Z = z) = \\frac{\\pi_0 f_0(z)}{f(z)}$$\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a **posterior probability**---the chance that a specific case with $z$-score $z$ is a false discovery.\n",
        "\n",
        "Contrast with the (tail-area) FDR, which is an expected proportion over a set of rejections.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "### Relationship\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{FDR}(z_0) = E[\\text{fdr}(Z) \\mid Z \\geq z_0] = \\frac{\\int_{z_0}^\\infty \\text{fdr}(z) f(z) \\, dz}{\\int_{z_0}^\\infty f(z) \\, dz}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The tail-area FDR is the average of the local FDR over the rejection region.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Connections to Bayesian Thinking\n",
        "\n",
        "The two-groups model is inherently Bayesian:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Prior**: $P(\\text{null}) = \\pi_0$\n",
        "- **Likelihood**: $f_0(z)$ under the null, $f_1(z)$ under the alternative\n",
        "- **Posterior**: $\\text{fdr}(z) = P(\\text{null} \\mid z)$\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "But it's **empirical Bayes**: instead of specifying a prior, we estimate $\\pi_0$ and $f_1$ from the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# When $N(0,1)$ Lies to You {.centered}\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Efron's Prostate Cancer Surprise\n",
        "\n",
        "Efron analyzed a prostate cancer microarray study (Singh et al., 2002): 6,033 genes, 102 patients.\n",
        "\n",
        "He converted the test statistics to $z$-scores expecting them to follow $N(0,1)$ under the null. Instead, the central peak of the histogram was **wider than expected**: the empirical null was closer to $N(\\hat{\\delta}_0, \\hat{\\sigma}_0^2)$ with $\\hat{\\sigma}_0 > 1$.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "Using the theoretical $N(0,1)$ null would overstate significance — genes whose $z$-scores fell in the inflated tails would be called discoveries when they were actually consistent with the (wider) true null.\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "**The \"empirical null\" saved the analysis** — and showed that blindly trusting $N(0,1)$ can be dangerous. The exact parameters depend on the dataset and estimation method; the key insight is that $\\hat{\\sigma}_0 \\neq 1$.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Empirical Null\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why the theoretical null might be wrong\n",
        "\n",
        "Efron observed that in many real datasets, the central peak of the $z$-score histogram is **wider** than $N(0,1)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Possible causes:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Unobserved covariates (batch effects, population structure)\n",
        "- Correlation among tests\n",
        "- Model misspecification\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "### Empirical null\n",
        "\n",
        "Fit $f_0(z) = N(\\hat{\\delta}_0, \\hat{\\sigma}_0^2)$ from the central part of the observed $z$-score distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "If $\\hat{\\sigma}_0 > 1$, the theoretical null is too narrow and we'd get too many false discoveries.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Empirical Null: Illustration"
      ],
