        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Efron's Estimation Procedure\n",
        "\n",
        "### Step by step (Efron, *Large-Scale Inference*, Ch. 4–5)\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Convert test statistics to $z$-scores: $z_i = \\Phi^{-1}(1 - p_i)$ or use the statistic directly\n",
        "2. Estimate $f(z)$ using Poisson regression on binned counts (Lindsey's method)\n",
        "3. Estimate $\\pi_0$ and $f_0$ (theoretical or empirical null)\n",
        "4. Compute $\\widehat{\\text{fdr}}(z) = \\hat{\\pi}_0 \\hat{f}_0(z) / \\hat{f}(z)$\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "The R package `locfdr` automates this.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## When Does This Work?\n",
        "\n",
        "### Requirements for empirical Bayes FDR\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Large $m$**: Need thousands of tests to estimate $f(z)$ well\n",
        "2. **Exchangeability**: Tests should be \"comparable\" (same type of measurement, similar noise structure)\n",
        "3. **Mixture model is reasonable**: The two-groups framework is a good approximation\n",
        "\n",
        ". . .\n",
        "\n",
        "### When it can fail\n",
        "\n",
        "- Small $m$ (say $< 100$): not enough data to estimate the mixture\n",
        "- Strong correlation structure that distorts the null distribution\n",
        "- Heterogeneous tests (mixing gene expression with methylation, for example)\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Multiple Testing in Practice: A Decision Framework\n",
        "\n",
        "```{mermaid}\n",
        "%%| fig-cap: \"Choosing an error rate\"\n",
        "flowchart TD\n",
        "    A[How many tests?] -->|Few: 1–20| B[Use FWER: Bonferroni or Holm]\n",
        "    A -->|Many: 100+| C{Goal?}\n",
        "    C -->|Confirmation| D[Use FWER: Bonferroni-Holm]\n",
        "    C -->|Discovery| E{How many tests?}\n",
        "    E -->|100–1000| F[BH or Storey q-values]\n",
        "    E -->|1000+| G[Efron local FDR / empirical Bayes]\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Software Ecosystem\n",
        "\n",
        "| Method | R | Python |\n",
        "|--------|---|--------|\n",
        "| Bonferroni / Holm | `p.adjust()` | `statsmodels.stats.multitest` |\n",
        "| Benjamini–Hochberg | `p.adjust(method=\"BH\")` | `multipletests(method='fdr_bh')` |\n",
        "| Storey $q$-values | `qvalue::qvalue()` | `-- (custom or qvalue port)` |\n",
        "| Local FDR | `locfdr::locfdr()` | `-- (custom implementation)` |\n",
        "| Empirical Bayes (limma) | `limma::eBayes()` | `-- (use R via rpy2)` |\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **BH procedure**: Simple, controls FDR under independence (or PRDS). Your go-to tool.\n",
        "2. **Storey's $q$-value**: Adaptive FDR control using $\\hat{\\pi}_0$. More powerful when many nulls.\n",
        "3. **Efron's two-groups model**: The foundational framework. The mixture $f = \\pi_0 f_0 + (1-\\pi_0)f_1$ unifies everything.\n",
        "4. **Local FDR**: A test-specific posterior probability of being null. The most informative single summary.\n",
        "5. **Empirical null**: Always check whether $f_0 = N(0,1)$ is reasonable. If not, estimate it.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Up Next\n",
        "\n",
        "**Lab 2**: Apply BH, $q$-values, and local FDR to a real gene-expression dataset."
